      "markdown": "TABLE 1 Demographics and clinical characteristics.\n\n| Variable (mean $\\pm$ SD) | Patients with AD |  | CON (n = 83) | $p$-value (post-hoc comparison) |\n| :--: | :--: | :--: | :--: | :--: |\n|  | REL (n = 59) | ABS (n = 28) |  |  |\n| Sex male/female | $52 / 7$ | $23 / 5$ | $70 / 13$ | $0.718^{a}$ |\n| Age in years | $45.50 \\pm 9.56$ | $43.48 \\pm 11.85$ | $43.40 \\pm 11.12$ | $0.490^{b}$ |\n| Education in years | $14.09 \\pm 3.27$ | $14.63 \\pm 3.81$ | $15.56 \\pm 3.19$ | $0.010^{c d}$ <br> (REL < CON) |\n| CIDI: Age of first drink | $14.66 \\pm 2.55$ | $15.18 \\pm 2.55$ | $14.71 \\pm 2.33$ | $0.766^{c}$ |\n| CIDI: Age of first time drunk | $16.64 \\pm 3.07$ | $16.29 \\pm 3.49$ | $16.71 \\pm 3.51$ | $0.578^{c}$ |\n| CIDI: Age of first binge-drinking episode | $30.67 \\pm 10.16$ | $32.39 \\pm 12.18$ | $21.54 \\pm 7.18$ | $<0.001^{c d}$ <br> (REL > CON, ABS > CON) |\n| CIDI: Alcohol consumption per day ( g ) | $178.85 \\pm 124.71$ | $151.98 \\pm 91.56$ | $11.74 \\pm 13.50$ | $<0.001^{c d}$ <br> (REL > CON, ABS > CON) |\n| CIDI: Alcohol consumption per occasion ( g ) | $205.63 \\pm 108.23$ | $176.79 \\pm 93.06$ | $44.46 \\pm 32.94$ | $<0.001^{c d}$ <br> (REL > CON, ABS > CON) |\n| CIDI: Alcohol consumption per binge-drinking episode ( g ) | $289.68 \\pm 165.99$ | $257.79 \\pm 123.11$ | $94.45 \\pm 96.12$ | $<0.001^{c d}$ <br> (REL > CON, ABS > CON) |\n| ADS: Addiction severity | $14.85 \\pm 6.42$ | $14.11 \\pm 7.29$ | $1.94 \\pm 2.89$ | $<0.001^{c d}$ <br> (REL > CON, ABS > CON) |\n| OCDS: Craving | $12.33 \\pm 8.46$ | $11.38 \\pm 8.31$ | $2.87 \\pm 2.98$ | $<0.001^{c d}$ <br> (REL > CON, ABS > CON) |\n| Time of alcohol abstinence before MRI scan in days | $24.58 \\pm 14.35$ | $20.39 \\pm 7.31$ | - | $0.328^{d}$ |\n| TLFB: Time until relapse in days | $130.90 \\pm 100.32$ | - | - | - |\n\nAbbreviations: ABS, abstaining patients with AD; AD, alcohol dependence; ADS, Alcohol Dependence Scale; CIDI, Composite International Diagnostic Interview; CON, controls; OCDS, Obsessive Compulsive Drinking Scale; REL, relapsing patients with AD; TLFB, Timeline-Follow-Back.\n${ }^{a}$ Chi-square $\\left(\\chi^{2}\\right)$ test.\n${ }^{\\text {b }}$ One-way ANOVA.\n${ }^{\\text {c }}$ Kruskal-Wallis test.\n${ }^{d}$ Mann-Whitney U test.\n${ }^{e}$ Bonferroni-corrected.\nnetwork, thus reflecting variance uniquely shared between two nodes, above and beyond ups and downs in functional connectivity that would be shared with other network nodes (in the linear modelling regime). ${ }^{39}$ In this way, partial correlation produces more accurate estimates of direct connectivity as compared with naïve, raw node-node correlation estimates, ${ }^{40,41}$ making it a pertinent method to investigate biologically informed alterations of network topology in disease populations. ${ }^{42}$\n\n## 2.6 | Network topology analysis\n\nTo reduce the possibility of bias due to a specific connection threshold, we applied a set of sparsity thresholds to the partial correlation matrices using a proportional threshold range of $0.10<k<0.50$ with intervals of 0.01 , where $k$ specifies the ratio of strongest edges that are maintained in the network relative to the maximum number of\npossible edges in the network. Thresholding can introduce network fragmentation, that is, splitting up the network into disconnected components where at least one node is not connected to any other node in the network, thereby confounding the computation of network topological parameters. In our study, we assessed network fragmentation for all subjects and thresholds using the function CheckFrag.m implemented in GraphVar 2.0. ${ }^{43,44}$\n\nThe topological properties of the undirected weighted network were calculated for each threshold, including global measures on network segregation (global clustering coefficient $C_{\\text {global }}$, global transitivity $T_{\\text {global }}$ ), network integration (global efficiency $E_{\\text {global }}$, global characteristic path length $L_{\\text {global }}$ ) and global connectivity strength $W_{\\text {global }}$. At the nodal level, we evaluated the topological centrality of each node as an indicator for its influence on the network. To this end, we calculated four different measures of nodal centrality, including nodal degree centrality $D_{\\text {nodal }}$, nodal strength centrality $W_{\\text {nodal }}$, nodal eigenvector centrality $E C_{\\text {nodal }}$ and nodal betweenness centrality"
    },
    {
      "markdown": "$B C_{\\text {nodal }}$. A detailed description of the global and nodal graph measures analysed in this study can be found in Table S1. Prior to the computation of graph topological metrics (except for $W_{\\text {global }}$ ), we scaled subject-level rsFC matrices by the maximum absolute weight to obviate confounds in network topology introduced through potential differences in weight distributions. To improve interpretability, subjectlevel graph metrics were additionally normalized by dividing the respective measure of the original network by the average of the same measure derived from 100 random networks with the same number of nodes and similar degree, weight and strength distributions (see function null_model_und_sign.m from Brain Connectivity Toolbox Version 2019-03-0315; available at https://sites.google.com/ site/bctnet/all-functions). For each normalized global and nodal graph measure, we computed the area under the curve (AUC) as an integrated score independent of a single threshold selection. Network analyses were performed using GraphVar 2.043,44 running under the MATLAB ${ }^{\\circledR}$ environment.\n\n## 2.7 | Statistical analysis\n\n### 2.7.1 | Group differences in global and local network topology\n\nGroup comparisons of global and nodal graph metrics between AD subgroups (REL, ABS) and CON were carried out using nonparametric permutation tests controlling for age, gender, site and education years. First, we computed the one-way ANOVA $F$-value testing for differences in the AUC of a given graph metric between groups. Next, we randomly shuffled the group labels between participants and re-calculated the $F$-value. We repeated this procedure 10000 times to create an empirical null distribution of the effect underlying group differences in AUC. Finally, we obtained a $p$-value by estimating the proportion of permutations that were equal to or exceeded the empirical $F$-value. Results were considered significant if actual effects exceeded those from the empirical null distribution according to the $p<0.05$ threshold. Global and nodal graph measures exhibiting significant group differences were further subjected to post-hoc analysis. Specifically, we computed the empirical differences in AUC between groups using two-sample $t$-tests, then permuted the group labels 10000 times, re-calculated the $t$-test and estimated the proportion of effects in the permutation-based null distribution that exceeded the empirical group effect. Results were considered significant if $p<0.05$. A false discovery rate (FDR) correction accounting for multiple testing was implemented for global and nodal metrics separately. For global metrics, we accounted for the number of global parameters and post-hoc group comparisons $(n=15)$ while for nodal metrics, we corrected for the number of parameters $(n=246)$ for each graph metric. To assess evidence for the null hypothesis, we also calculated the Bayes factor for each group contrast based on $t$-tests with a JZS prior $(r=\\sqrt{ } 2 / 2)$ using the BayesFactor package in $\\mathbb{R}^{45}$ and scaled the corresponding values using a $\\log 10$ transform.\n\n### 2.7.2 | Group differences in functional connectivity\n\nWe applied the Network-Based Statistic (NBS) approach22 to the fully connected partial correlation matrices to identify differences in rsFC between groups. Briefly, significantly altered subnetworks, defined in terms of connected graph components, were determined by incorporating an edge-by-edge comparison of rsFC based on a one-way ANOVA with $F>4.8(p<0.01)$. Within the identified subnetworks, post-hoc twosample $t$-tests were conducted to detect significantly altered components between specific groups. In our study, we used an initial link threshold of $t_{\\text {initial }}=3.1$ to identify suprathreshold links. Since NBS highly depends on the initial cluster-defining threshold, we additionally tested a range of different link thresholds ( $t_{\\text {initial }}=2.9-3.3$ ). To estimate the significance of the identified components, we generated an empirical null distribution of maximal component sizes by randomly permuting the group assignments 10,000 times and calculating the proportion of permutations in which the maximal component size exceeded the size of the observed component. Components (i.e., subnetworks) were considered significant if $p<0.05$, FWE-corrected.\n\n### 2.7.3 | Brain-behaviour relationships\n\nTo investigate associations between putative alterations in network topological parameters and clinical variables, we used partial correlation controlling for age, gender, site and education years. In case of non-normality of clinical and graph topological variables as determined by Shapiro-Wilk tests ( $p<0.05$ ), we computed Spearman's partial rank correlation. FDR correction determined over the number of significantly altered network metrics was applied to account for multiple testing.\n\nAdditionally, we performed survival analyses to incorporate patients with AD with censored relapse data. Specifically, we calculated Cox proportional hazards models to examine the association between altered network topological measures and time to relapse. For sensitivity analyses, the statistical models were adjusted for age, gender, site and years of education. The proportional hazards assumption was tested based on scaled Schoenfeld residuals. Network parameters and covariates were z-standardized to facilitate interpretability and comparability of hazard ratios (HR). To account for multiple testing, FDR correction was applied. Survival analyses were carried out using IBM SPSS for Windows 27.0 (IBM Corp, Armonk, NY, USA).\n\n## 3 | RESULTS\n\n### 3.1 | Sample characteristics\n\nOne subject was excluded from further analyses because of severe network fragmentation. As a result, 59 relapsing patients with AD (REL), 28 abstaining patients with AD (ABS) and 83 control subjects (CON) were included in the final analyses (Table 1). No significant differences in age and sex distributions were observed in any of the"
    },
    {
      "markdown": "group comparisons. REL reported fewer years of education compared with CON. As expected, both AD subgroups reported significantly more alcohol consumption (per day, per drinking occasion and per binge-drinking episode), higher addiction severity (ADS) and higher alcohol craving (OCDS) compared with CON. Interestingly, CON experienced their first binge-drinking episode at an earlier age compared with both patient subgroups. No significant differences could be observed between REL and ABS on any demographic or clinical outcome (Table 1). Finally, no significant differences in head motion were observed between groups $(H[2]=2.75, p=0.253)$.\n\n## 3.2 | Global topology of functional brain networks\n\nREL exhibited decreased $W_{\\text {global }}\\left(p_{\\text {FDR }}=0.042\\right)$, increased $C_{\\text {global }}$ $\\left(p_{\\text {FDR }}=0.004\\right)$, increased $T_{\\text {global }}\\left(p_{\\text {FDR }}=0.004\\right)$, decreased $E_{\\text {global }}$ $\\left(p_{\\text {FDR }}=0.039\\right)$ and increased $L_{\\text {global }}\\left(p_{\\text {FDR }}=0.039\\right)$ compared with CON, suggesting a more segregated and less integrated network topology in REL with overall decreased network strength (Figure 1A). No significant differences were found between ABS and REL as well as between ABS and CON on any graph measure after FDR correction. These findings were consistent when additionally accounting for effects of head motion and for the number of days between withdrawal and fMRI scan (Table S3). Bayes Factor indices based on $t$-tests\ncorroborated results from frequentist analyses. Specifically, we found moderate to strong evidence for differences between REL and CON across all global graph measures, while no such evidence was found for the comparison of REL vs. ABS (Table S2). Moreover, in line with our hypotheses, comparing ABS vs. CON consistently yielded anecdotal or moderate evidence for the null hypothesis across all global graph measures (Table S2).\n\n## 3.3 | Nodal centrality\n\nAt the nodal level, we identified those brain regions that displayed significant group differences based on frequentist analysis ( $p<0.05$, 10000 permutations, FDR-corrected) as well as strong evidence for group differences based on Bayes Factor indices $\\left(B F_{X q(10)}+1\\right)$ for any nodal graph measure. In this regard, REL exhibited decreased nodal strength centrality ( $W_{\\text {nodal }}$ ) in 12 cortical and 10 subcortical brain regions compared with CON. The strongest evidence for reduced nodal strength centrality was observed in the left putamen (Table 2). Moreover, REL displayed decreased nodal eigenvector centrality $\\left(E C_{\\text {nodal }}\\right)$ in five subcortical brain regions compared with CON, with the strongest evidence for group differences in the left ventromedial putamen (Table 2). We found no differences between REL and CON in degree centrality and betweenness centrality. Comparing REL vs. ABS and ABS vs. CON yielded no differences in any nodal\n![img-0.jpeg](img-0.jpeg)\n\nFIGURE 1 A) Global network organization in relapsing patients with AD (REL, dark red), abstaining patients with AD (ABS, light red) and controls (CON, blue), indicating decreased network strength and more segregated and less integrated network topology in REL compared with CON. B) Partial correlations (controlling for age, gender, site and education years) between altered graph measures in REL and the time until the first relapse (measured using Timeline-Follow-Back, TLFB) show that earlier relapse is associated with decreased network strength, increased network segregation and decreased network integration. * $p<0.05$, ** $p<0.01$ after FDR correction. Abbreviations: AD, alcohol dependence; FDR, false discovery rate."
