n$H R=1.48,95 \\% C I=1.16-1.89, p=0.002 ; T_{\\text {global }}: H R=1.47,95 \\%$ $\\mathrm{CI}=1.15-1.88, p=0.002$ ).\n\nFinally, increased global network segregation was associated with higher levels of self-reported craving in REL ( $C_{\\text {global }}: r=0.29$, $p=0.033 ; T_{\\text {global }}: r=0.30, p=0.029$ ); however, these associations did not survive multiple testing corrections. No significant associations were observed between altered network topological parameters and either severity of AD (Table S6) or other variables of alcohol use during follow-up (Table S7).\n\n## 3.5 Network-based statistics\n\nNBS analysis revealed a predominantly left-hemispheric subnetwork of significantly decreased rsFC in REL compared with CON ( $p_{\\text {FWE }}=0.015$ ), comprising eight nodes and seven edges. Specifically, REL exhibited decreased rsFC mainly between the precuneus"
